    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7b600053_a84ab226",
        "filename": "skolo/go/swarming_token/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 17,
      "author": {
        "id": 5120
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-26T20:59:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Probably not important, but why every 4 minutes? Aren\u0027t the tokens valid for 60 minutes and refreshed every 45 minutes, meaning there\u0027s a 15 minute grace period?\n\nAlso consider this approach: https://skia.googlesource.com/buildbot/+/e52fe456c0693f0853d7092c3826dcf499cbbf33/pulld/go/pulld/pull.go#113",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 17,
        "startChar": 24,
        "endLine": 17,
        "endChar": 33
      },
      "revId": "7c551bf0e143fb0c7d418bcc4255ba19ba311bca",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d684ed85_f49e3bfd",
        "filename": "skolo/go/swarming_token/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 17,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-29T13:55:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The tokens are valid for 60 minutes and regenerated and written to disk by get_oauth2_token every 45 minutes.  In order to ensure that the token served by metadata_server is always valid, metadata_server reads the token from disk every 10 minutes.  I chose that number because it\u0027s a nice, round number which is less than the gap between 45 and 60; if it were greater, we might end up with periods of time in which the token we serve is no longer valid.  The 4-minute period for reading the token from metadata was chosen in the same way: it\u0027s a little less than the gap between 10 minutes and 15 (60-45).\n\nThere are pros and cons to the approach used by pulld.  The biggest con is that this program would need to be a long-running process, which I trust significantly less than a cron job in a situation where we have no monitoring.  In an ideal world we\u0027d have monitoring on all of the bots anyway though.  And for true compatibility with the GCE metadata server, maybe we should add wait_for_change support anyway.",
      "parentUuid": "7b600053_a84ab226",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 17,
        "startChar": 24,
        "endLine": 17,
        "endChar": 33
      },
      "revId": "7c551bf0e143fb0c7d418bcc4255ba19ba311bca",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bc172ee4_22f5350c",
        "filename": "skolo/go/swarming_token/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 17,
      "author": {
        "id": 5120
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-29T15:49:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Ok, SG, I forgot the 10 minute delay.\n\n(The rest of this comment is just me spamming thoughts and not necessarily meant as a request to change this CL.)\n\nRegarding monitoring: I think our existing monitoring for quarantined/dead bots should alert us when there is a problem, right?\n\nFor cron vs. systemd, I\u0027m not sure I see much difference in terms of monitoring. At this point I\u0027m more familiar with systemd than with cron, so I would know where to look if things went wrong. The one caveat is that cron will blindly continue to run something that continuously fails while systemd will stop trying after a few attempts. (I think the cron approach is preferable in this case.)\n\nFor Scheduled Tasks vs. Service on Windows, my experience is that scheduled tasks are a bit difficult to debug (although that\u0027s probably mostly because logging of scheduled tasks is off by default). OTOH, I have no idea how to set up a service.",
      "parentUuid": "d684ed85_f49e3bfd",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 17,
        "startChar": 24,
        "endLine": 17,
        "endChar": 33
      },
      "revId": "7c551bf0e143fb0c7d418bcc4255ba19ba311bca",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
